man ls -p

Description: Append / to directory names when listing.
Example: ls -p → docs/ file.txt
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -p
Desktop/  Documents/  Downloads/ Music/  Pictures/  Public/  Templates/  Videos/

man ls -q

Description: Print non-printable characters as ?.
Useful if filenames have weird chars.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -q
Desktop  Documents  Downloads  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -r

Description: Reverse order of sorting.
Example: ls -r → last file first.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -r
Videos  Templates  Public  Pictures  Music   Downloads  Documents  Desktop

man ls -s

Description: Print the allocated size (blocks) of each file.
Example: ls -s file.txt
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -s
total 44
4 Desktop  4 Documents  4 Downloads  4 Music  4 Pictures  4 Public  4 Templates  4 Videos
man ls -t

Description: Sort files by modification time (newest first).
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -t
Downloads  Desktop  Documents  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -u

Description: Sort files by last access time.
With -l, show the access time instead of modification.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -u
 Music  Pictures  Public  Videos  Documents  Downloads  Desktop  Templates 

man ls -v

Description: Sort files naturally by version (e.g., file1, file2, file10).
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -v
Desktop  Documents  Downloads  Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos  

man ls -w

Description: Set the line width for displaying multiple columns.
Example: ls -w 50
ls -w 50
Desktop      Music     Templates
Documents   Pictures  Videos
Downloads    Public

man ls -x

Description: List files in columns, sorted horizontally.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -x   
Desktop  Documents  Downloads   Music  Pictures  Public  Templates  Videos

man ls -y

 Not available (skipped, not in GNU ls).

man ls -Z

Description: Display each file’s SELinux security context (if enabled).
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ ls -Z
? Desktop  ? Documents  ? Downloads  ? Music  ? Pictures  ? Public  ? Templates  ? Videos



Activity 1:
part 2
whoami

Prints the current logged-in user’s name.
Example: whoami 
neeharika

pwd

Prints the present working directory (current folder path).
Example: /home/neeharika

cd

Change directory. Without arguments, goes to home directory.
Example: cd : /home/neeharika
cd Documents
/home/neeharika/Documents

cd /

Changes to the root directory (/).

cd ..

Goes one level up from current directory.
Example: /home/neeharika/Downloads => cd .. => /home/neeharika

cd <path>

Change to the given path.
Example: cd /etc=> current directory is /etc.

Activity 1:
part B:
tree command
tree -l -L 1

Show directory tree with symbolic links (-l), depth limited to 1 level.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 1
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos


tree -l -L 2

Same, but show 2 levels deep.
(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 2
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos

8 directories, 0 files


tree -l -L 3

Same, but show 3 levels deep.
                                                                                                                        
┌──(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree -l -L 3           
.
├── Desktop
├── Documents
├── Downloads
├── Music
├── Pictures
├── Public
├── Templates
└── Videos


tree /var/log/apt -La 1

Show contents of /var/log/apt, including hidden files (-a), limit depth to 1, and follow symlinks (-l).
─(neeharika㉿kali)-[~]
└─$ tree /var/log/apt -La 1
/var/log/apt
├── eipp.log.xz
├── history.log
├── history.log.1.gz
├── term.log
└── term.log.1.gz

1 directory, 5 files
